<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Sound Effect Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Play a selected Sound FX or Music entry when mission logic reaches the right trigger, such as an objective dependency or a nearby player interaction.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What Sound Effect Event Points Do
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A <Bold>Sound Effect</Bold> Event Point plays an audio entry from the game's sound list.
        It can be used for mission feedback, interaction sounds, alarms, stingers, music cues, or
        short audio moments that need to be tied to mission scripting.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Sound Effect Event Points do not describe the objective by themselves. They are usually
        supporting feedback: another Event Point becomes active, the player uses something nearby,
        or the mission reaches a scripted moment, and the sound plays to reinforce that event.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Practical meaning:</Run>
                <Run> Use Sound Effect for audible feedback. Pair it with Message, Conversation, Visual Effect, Activate Prim, or objective logic when the player also needs context.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Sound Effect uses the standard Event Point common properties: index number, Event Point
        type, letter group, colour, position, facing direction, trigger settings, and listening mode.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The index number and Event Point type are automatic. Letter group and colour are useful for
        keeping the sound cue grouped with the objective, prop, conversation, or area that causes it.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Position
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Position matters when the trigger is spatial, such as <Bold>Player Uses Radius</Bold>. It
        can also matter if the engine treats the selected audio as positional. Place the Event Point
        at the source of the sound or at the interaction point that should cause the sound to play.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Trigger Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Trigger settings decide when the sound plays. A dependency-triggered sound waits for another
        Event Point. A player-use radius sound plays when the player uses/interacts within the
        configured radius.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Sound Effect-Specific Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Sound Effect has two type-specific settings. These map directly to the original sound setup:
        <Bold>Data[0]</Bold> stores the sound category, and <Bold>Data[1]</Bold> stores the absolute
        index into <Bold>sound_list[]</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Category</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Category chooses whether the entry is treated as <Bold>Sound FX</Bold> or <Bold>Music</Bold>.
        The editor filters the sound list to match this category. Use <Bold>Sound FX</Bold> for most
        short mission cues, interaction sounds, alarms, and feedback. Use <Bold>Music</Bold> only
        when intentionally selecting a music entry.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Sound / Sound ID</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        The sound list selection writes the absolute <Bold>Sound ID</Bold> into the Event Point.
        You can choose the sound from the list or type the Sound ID directly. The ID is not a local
        filtered-list index; it is the original index into the game's full <Bold>sound_list[]</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Authoring tip:</Run>
                <Run> Pick the Category first, then choose the Sound. Changing the category changes the filtered list, but the stored Sound ID remains the absolute sound_list index.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        How Missions Trigger Sound Effects
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Existing Sound Effect usage is mostly tied to another Event Point becoming active or to the
        player using something in a small radius. Useful trigger patterns are:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Dependency</Bold> - plays the sound after another Event Point has fired.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Player Uses Radius</Bold> - plays the sound when the player uses/interacts within range.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Active</Bold> - useful for one-shot sounds that should fire when the trigger becomes true.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Active While</Bold> - useful when the sound should be tied to a condition that remains true, but this can repeat if the trigger is not controlled carefully.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Critical trigger detail:</Run>
                <Run> Be careful with Active While. If the condition stays true, the sound may behave like a repeated or sustained cue depending on engine handling and the selected sound.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Sound Effect Patterns
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Sound After Mission Progress</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Dependency</Bold> when the sound should play after another Event Point completes.
        This is useful for feedback after an objective, scripted state change, camera moment, or
        interaction chain.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>MIB.ucm</Bold>, Sound Effect <Bold>20</Bold> uses <Bold>Sound FX</Bold> with Sound
        ID <Bold>17</Bold>. It is triggered by <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on Event Point
        <Bold>17</Bold> and uses <Bold>Active While</Bold>, tying the sound cue to that earlier
        mission condition.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Create the Event Point that represents the mission event first. Then create the Sound Effect,
        choose the Category and Sound ID, set <Bold>Triggered By</Bold> to <Bold>Dependency</Bold>,
        and set <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> to the Event Point that should cause the sound.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Interaction Sound</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Player Uses Radius</Bold> when the player should hear a sound after using an
        object, console, switch, door, or other nearby interaction point.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>skymiss2.ucm</Bold>, Sound Effect <Bold>72</Bold> uses <Bold>Sound FX</Bold> with
        Sound ID <Bold>174</Bold>. It is triggered by <Bold>Player Uses Radius</Bold> with radius
        <Bold>128</Bold>, so the player must interact near the Event Point for the sound to play.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Place the Sound Effect Event Point at the interaction location. Set the trigger to
        <Bold>Player Uses Radius</Bold>, choose a radius that matches the object or area, then select
        the Sound FX or Music entry that should play.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Objective Feedback Sound</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use a dependency-triggered sound alongside a Message, Visual Effect, Activate Prim, or
        Counter chain when the player needs immediate audio confirmation that something happened.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Decide which Event Point represents the completed action. Trigger the Sound Effect from that
        Event Point, then add any supporting Message or Visual Effect separately. Keep all related
        Event Points in the same colour and letter group for easier debugging.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Basic Sound Effect Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Decide what mission action should cause the sound.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add a <Bold>Sound Effect</Bold> Event Point.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Choose <Bold>Sound FX</Bold> or <Bold>Music</Bold> in Category.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select the sound from the list or enter the absolute <Bold>Sound ID</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Place the Event Point at the sound source or interaction location if the trigger is spatial.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the trigger, usually <Bold>Dependency</Bold> or <Bold>Player Uses Radius</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Use <Bold>Active</Bold> for a normal one-shot cue unless you specifically need Active While behaviour.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test the sound in game to confirm timing, repetition, and volume feel correct.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Final checklist:</Run>
                <Run> Category is correct, Sound ID points at the intended sound_list entry, the trigger fires at the right mission moment, and Active While is only used when repeated or condition-linked audio is intentional.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>
